result.execSummary:
The defendant James A. Pagenkopf was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • 3rd Degree Sexual Assault, a class G felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.225(3).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes: Costs to be paid directly to the Waushara County Clerk of Court within 60 days or establish a payment plan.  Failure to pay may result in suspension of your driver's license, tax intercept, a civil judgment being entered against you, a warrant being issued for your arrest for contempt and/or the debt being turned over to a collection agency.

The defendant is to have NO CONTACT with J.S.S, as named in the complaint.   The defendant must maintain absolute sobriety, may not be present upon the premises of any bars, and is prohibited from possessing/ingesting any impairing substances that have not been prescribed by a physician.

Defendant to comply with the Sex Offender Registration Program.  Complete a Sex Offender Treatment Assessment and comply with any further counseling and/or treatment as deemed appropriate by the Supervising Agent. Court orders registry for 15 years after supervision is completed.  Defendant is to comply with any rules/recommendations as deemed appropriate by the supervising agent.   DNA sample to be provided and surcharge assessed.

timeConds.notes: With Huber. No Good Time Credit.

2:38 pm case called. Defendant James A. Pagenkopf in court with attorney Ben Szilagyi.  Scott C. Blader appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Court goes over motion on for hearing today. State has filed an objection to the request. Court makes a statment to counsel and has read the briefs filed. Argument by DA Blader. Argument by Attorney Szilagyi. Statement by Court. Court enters an order where the victim through her guardian can object to information be provided; however, if victim objects to information being revealed-she will then be prohibited from testifying. Court directs records relating to the victims mental health condition and her level of cognition in relation to any Chapter 54 factors. Attorney Zouski questions court regarding order. Further statement by Court-will not order an additional evaluation-Court states the order is regarding what exists. Court orders incamera inspection of any treatment records that relate to her mental capacity. Court will then determine what will or will not be discovered. Court discusses the declination of victim regarding information to be revealed. Victim will have an opportunity to impede the court's review and can impede the defense's review of records. Court states records from 2010 forward. Court makes a statement regarding records and would be willing to go to where the records are located instead of having the documents reproduced. Further argument by Attorney Szilagyi. Further statement by Court. Further argument by State. Court makes statement regarding records. Court holds in abeayance determination regarding DHS records. Court directs Attorney Szilagyi to draft an order for courts signature. Statement by DA Blader regarding order and letter to guardian.  Status conference scheduled for August 30, 2016 at 09:00 am.
